1 Introduction

The R package sf (Pebesma 2022a) (successor of sp) is a popular package allowing manipulation of spatial data in R. It is used to represent and work with spatial vector data including points, polygons, and lines, and their associated information. sf package uses sf objects that are extensions of data frames containing a collection of simple features or spatial objects with possibly associated data.

sf package mainly represent spatial data in vector data forms.

2 Vector data

Vector data form is used to display points, lines, and polygons, and possibly associated information. For example, locations of monitoring stations, road networks, or municipalities of a country.

Vector data are often represented using a data storage format called shapefile.

A shapefile has three mandatory files

  • .shp contains the geometry data

  • .shx a positional index of the geometry data that allows to seek forward and backward the .shp file

  • .dbf stores the attributes for each shape

E.g., check out the default R datasets available in your directory. Focus on the North Carolina SIDC shapefiles nc. * available from nc {sf}.

rm(list = ls())

3 The R package sf and some common functions

The sf (Pebesma 2022a) (the successor of sp) is a popular R package allowing manipulation of spatial data in R. It can be used to represent and work with spatial vector data including points, polygons, and lines, and their associated information. The sf package uses sf objects that are extensions of data frames containing a collection of simple features or spatial objects with possibly associated data.

Common functions to manipulate sf objects include the following:

  • st_read() reads a sf object,

  • st_write() writes a sf object,

  • st_crs() gets or sets a new coordinate reference system (CRS),

  • st_transform() transforms data to a new CRS,

  • st_intersection() intersects sf objects,

  • st_union() combines several sf objects into one,

  • st_simplify() simplifies a sf object,

  • st_coordinates() retrieves coordinates of a sf object,

  • st_as_sf() converts a foreign object to a sf object.

Below we will introduce the most important of them however, feel free to have a look at them at home

4 Reading/printing vector data via sf

The following script uses st_read {sf} to read/retrieve the spatial data set nc{sf} from R package sf.

rm(list = ls())
#
library(sf)
#
path.to.nc.shp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                       package = "sf")
#
map <- st_read(path.to.nc.shp, 
               quiet = TRUE)

The script below shows that st_read {sf} returns a sf object which is a data.frame with the attributives and the geometry.

class(map)
## [1] "sf"         "data.frame"
head(map)

In general, A sf object contains the following objects of class sf, sfc and sfg:

  • sf (simple feature): each row of the data.frame is a single simple feature consisting of attributes and geometry.

  • sfc (simple feature geometry list-column): the geometry column of the data.frame is a list-column of class sfc with the geometry of each simple feature.

  • sfg (simple feature geometry): each of the rows of the sfc list-column corresponds to the simple feature geometry (sfg) of a single simple feature.

Function st_geometry {sf} is used to get, set, replace or rename geometry from an sf object.

The following script displays the geometry of an sf object.

rm( list = ls() )
library(sf)
path.to.nc.shp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                       package = "sf")
nc.map <- st_read(path.to.nc.shp, 
               quiet = TRUE)
nc.geometry <- st_geometry(nc.map)
print(nc.geometry)
## Geometry set for 100 features 
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -84.32385 ymin: 33.88199 xmax: -75.45698 ymax: 36.58965
## Geodetic CRS:  NAD27
## First 5 geometries:

5 Making maps with sf objects

5.1 By using ggplot2

The ggplot2 package (Wickham, Chang, et al.2022) allows to create graphics based on the grammar of graphics, allowing users to build plots layer by layer.

To create a plot with ggplot2, call ggplot() specifying arguments data which is a data frame with the variables to plot, and mapping +aes() which are aesthetic mappings between variables in the data and visual properties of the objects in the graph such as position and color of points or lines.

Use + to add layers of graphical components to the graph.

Add objects to the graph with geom_*() functions (e.g, geom_point() for points, geom_line() for lines).

You can create maps by using the geom_sf() function and providing a simple feature sf object.

The script below prints the map of variable SID74 (sudden infant deaths) from the North Carolina SIDS data set nc {sf}.

rm( list = ls() )
#
# Load spatial data
#
library(sf)
path.to.nc.shp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                       package = "sf")
nc.map <- st_read(path.to.nc.shp, 
               quiet = TRUE)
#
# Load package
#
library(ggplot2)
# 
# Create an   Map for the attribute SID74
#
ggplot(nc.map) +                   # sf object holding the spatial data to be plotted
  geom_sf(aes(fill = SID74)) +     # the name of the variable I wish to map as colour  
  ggtitle("North Carolina SIDS data") +
  xlab("x") +
  ylab("y")

5.2 By using mapview

R package mapview (Appelhans et al.2022) allows to create interactive maps.

We just need to use the mapview() function passing as arguments the spatial object and the variable we want to plot.

Some arguments:

  • zcol= specifies the attribute to be plotted

  • map.types= the base maps. Some options can be found by running mapviewGetOption(basemaps).

The following script creates an interactive map with the variable SID74.

rm( list = ls() )
#
# Load spatial data
#
library(sf)
path.to.nc.shp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                       package = "sf")
nc.map <- st_read(path.to.nc.shp, 
               quiet = TRUE)
#
# Load package
#
library(mapview)
# 
# Create an Interactive Map for the attribute SID74
#
mapview(nc.map,        # sf object holdign the spatial data to be plotted 
        zcol = "SID74", # attribute name(s) or column number(s) in attribute table of the column(s) to be rendered.
        map.types = "CartoDB.Positron")

5.2.1 By using tmap

R package tmap (Tennekes 2022) creates static and interactive maps composed of multiple shapes and layers, and with different styles. Syntax is similar to that of ggplot2.

Maps are created with tm_shape() specifying the sf object.

Layers are added with a +tm_*() function. For example, +tm_polygons() draws polygons, +tm_dots() draws dots, and +tm_text() adds text. Basemap can be set by adding +tm_basemap() whose values are available from https://leaflet-extras.github.io/leaflet-providers/preview/

Functions tmap_mode(plot) and tmap_mode(view) can be used to set the static and interactive modes of the maps respectively.

Function tmap_save() can be used to save maps by specifying the name of the HTML file (if view mode) or image (if plot mode).

For more run ?tmap.

rm(list = ls())
#
# Get the spatial data
#
library(sf)
pathshp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", package = "sf")
nc.data <- st_read(pathshp, quiet = TRUE)
nc.map <- nc.data
#
# Load the library
#
library(tmap)
#
# Set the mode: "plot" or "view"
#
tmap_mode("plot")
#
# Create the thematic map
#
tm_shape(nc.map) + 
  tm_polygons("SID74")

6 Transforming point data to sf object

We wish to create a sf object from a data.frame containing the coordinates of locations and attributes.

To do that, use the function st_as_sf{sf} passing the object you wish to convert and specifying in argument coords the name of the data.frame columns containing the point coordinates.

Steps:

  1. use data.frame() to save the spatial data in a standard data.frame containing coordinates long and lat and two variables place and value.

  2. use function st_as_sf{sf} to turn a data.frame to a sf object.

  3. use function st_crs{sf} to set the coordinate reference system (CRS) to represent longitude and latitude coordinates.

  • Coordinate reference system (CRS) defines, with the help of coordinates, how the two-dimensional, projected map is related to real locations on the earth. In our course the code for CRS will be given.

The following script transforms some spatial data in data.frame form into sf object with CRS given by the EPSG code 4326.

rm(list=ls())
#
# Create data frame
#
df.data <- data.frame(
  place = c("London", "Paris", "Madrid", "Rome"),
  long = c(-0.118092, 2.349014, -3.703339, 12.496366),
  lat = c(51.509865, 48.864716, 40.416729, 41.902782),
  value = c(200, 300, 400, 500))
class(df.data)
## [1] "data.frame"
#
# Load the library
#
library(sf)
#
# transform data.frame into sf object 
#
sf.data <- st_as_sf( x = df.data,          #  enter data
                 coords = c("long", "lat"), # specify the coordinates
                 crs = 4326
                 )
st_crs(sf.data) <- 4326
#
# Plot
#
mapview(sf.data)

7 Creating sf objects (more advanced)

Recall that a sf object contains the following objects of class sf, sfc and sfg.

Simple feature geometries sfg objects can be of type POINT (single point), MULTIPOINT (set of points) or POLYGON (polygon), and can be created with st_point(), st_multipoint() and st_polygon().

Function st_sf{sf} creates an sf object by providing a data.frame with the attributes of each feature, and a simple feature geometry list-column sfc containing simple feature geometries sfg.

General steps:

  1. create the simple feature geometry objects sfg of type POINT, MULTIPOINT, and POLYGON.

  2. use st_sfc() to create a simple feature geometry list-column sfc with the sfg objects.

  3. use st_sf() to put the data.frame with the attribute and the simple feature geometry list-column sfc together.

The script below creates a sf object containing two single points, a set of points, and a polygon, with one attribute. Then it maps the object via ggplot2 for you to see the result.

rm( list = ls() )
library(sf)
#
# STEP 1
#
# Single point (point as a vector)
p1_sfg <- st_point(c(2, 2))     # a point
p2_sfg <- st_point(c(2.5, 3))   # a point
#
# Set of points (points as a matrix)
p <- rbind(c(6, 2), c(6.1, 2.6), c(6.8, 2.5),
           c(6.2, 1.5), c(6.8, 1.8))
mp_sfg <- st_multipoint(p)      # several points defined together 
#
# Polygon. Sequence of points that form a closed,
# non-self intersecting ring.
# The first ring denotes the exterior ring,
# zero or more subsequent rings denote holes in the exterior ring
p1 <- rbind(c(10, 0), c(11, 0), c(13, 2),
            c(12, 4), c(11, 4), c(10, 0))           # exterior ring  
p2 <- rbind(c(11, 1), c(11, 2), c(12, 2), c(11, 1)) # interior ring  
pol_sfg <- st_polygon(list(p1, p2))
#
# STEP 2
#
# Create sf object
p_sfc <- st_sfc(p1_sfg, 
                p2_sfg, 
                mp_sfg, 
                pol_sfg
                )
#
# STEP 3
#
df <- data.frame( v1 = c("A", "B", "C", "D") ) # the attributes  
p_sf <- st_sf(df,                              # the attributes
              geometry = p_sfc                 # the geometry 
              )
#
# Plot them (to be introduced later in the computer practical)
#
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(p_sf) + 
  geom_sf( aes( col = v1 ), size = 3)

# plot(p_sf)

8 Deleting and combining polygons

Let nc.map be the sf object.

The following script creates nc.map.1 from nc.map by removing polygons (areas) associated with the FIPS values 37125, 37051.

rm( list = ls() )
library(sf)
path.to.nc.shp <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                       package = "sf")
nc.map <- st_read(path.to.nc.shp, 
               quiet = TRUE)
#
# Delete polygon
#
nc.map.1 <- nc.map[-which(nc.map$FIPS %in% c("37125", "37051")), ]
#
# Plot it
#
plot(nc.map.1["AREA"])

The following script creates nc.map.2 as a union of all nc.map.1 polygons (remember we had removed some)

#
# Union
#
nc.map.2 <- st_union(nc.map.1, by_feature = FALSE)
nc.map.2 <- st_sf( nc.map.2 )
#
# Plot it
#
ggplot(st_union(nc.map.2, by_feature = FALSE)) + 
  geom_sf()

9 Counting the number of points within polygons

The following script:

  1. uses function st_sample {sf} to sample random points at locations in the map.

  2. uses function st_intersects{sf} to count the number of points within the polygons of a sf object. The returned object is a list with feature ids intersected in each of the polygons.

  3. uses function lengths{sf} to calculate the number of points inside each feature.

rm(list=ls())
library(sf)
# Map with divisions (sf object)
nc.map <- read_sf(system.file("shape/nc.shp", 
                              package = "sf")
                  )
#
# 1 
#
# Points over map (simple feature geometry list-column sfc)
nc.points <- st_sample(nc.map, 
                    size = 100)

# Map of points within polygons
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = nc.map) + 
  geom_sf(data = nc.points)

#
# 2 
#
# Intersection (first argument map, then points)
nc.inter <- st_intersects(nc.map, nc.points)
#
# 3 
#
# Add point count to each polygon
nc.map$count <- lengths(nc.inter)

# Map of number of points within polygons
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(nc.map) + geom_sf(aes(fill = count))
